## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

### 1. Metric Gaming

If the agent can improve the score without improving the actual quality, your metric is broken. Example: an “accuracy” score that only counts easy predictions.

**Fix:** Include adversarial dimensions. Make the metric multidimensional so gaming one dimension hurts another.

### 2. Complexity Creep

Without the simplicity criterion, the methodology grows endlessly. More layers, more sources, more analysis, more noise.

**Fix:** Regularly run “simplification experiments” — try REMOVING something and see if the metric holds.

### 3. Recency Bias

Only optimizing for the last few data points instead of the full history.

**Fix:** Score against a trailing window (e.g., 20 runs), not just the last one.

### 4. Experiment Paralysis

Spending more time designing experiments than running them.

**Fix:** The first experiment should be trivially simple. “Add X to the report.” Run it, measure, move on. Speed > perfection.

### 5. Human in the Loop Too Often

If the human has to approve every experiment, the loop stalls whenever the human is busy.

**Fix:** Make the auto-evolve boundary generous. Most formatting and sourcing changes are safe to auto-evolve. Reserve human approval for structural changes only.

